<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: ORANGE; 
</P>
<P>
CANDIDATES PLAN TO ATTEND 2 FORUMS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARY HELEN BERG 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
City Council and mayoral candidates will discuss issues and field questions 
from the public at two forums set for this week at Chapman College and the 
Orange Senior Citizens Community Center. 
</P>
<P>
The five mayoral candidates are: E. William Berke, financial consultant; 
incumbent City Councilman Gene Beyer, a retired principal; Robert A. Boice, a 
businessman and founder of the Old Towne Preservation Assn.; Marshall F. 
Norris, a retired Orange County clerk and former lieutenant in the Orange 
County Sheriff's Department, and Juan Pablo Serrano-Nieblas, an environmental 
engineer for UCI Medical Center. 
</P>
<P>
Running for City Council are: incumbent Joanne Coontz, the first woman elected 
to the Orange City Council; incumbent William Steiner, executive director of 
Orangewood Children's Foundation, and Don Greek, a civil engineer and former 
planning commissioner. 
</P>
<P>
The event, hosted by the Chamber of Commerce, will begin at 7 p.m. tonight in 
the Hashinger Lecture Hall at Chapman College, 333 N. Glassell St. The forum 
will also be carried live by Cablevision of Orange, Channel 17. 
</P>
<P>
Each candidate will have three minutes to make introductory remarks and one 
minute to respond to each question from the audience. 
</P>
<P>
Steve Ostrin, a member of the Chamber of Commerce Board of Directors, will 
moderate. Admission is free. For more information, call (714) 538-3581. 
</P>
<P>
The candidates will also appear at 10:30 a.m. Friday at the Orange Senior 
Citizens Community Center, 170 S. Olive St. This forum is open to the public 
but questions will be accepted from members of senior center only. For more 
information, call (714) 538-9633. MARY HELEN BERG 
</P>
</TEXT>
